(520, 1, '2025-12-03 21:54:50', '2025-12-04 02:54:50', 'Sakela Udhauli is one of the most significant festivals of the Kirat (Rai) community in Nepal and the eastern Himalayan region, celebrated annually during the full moon of Mangsir (November–December) as the harvest and winter-welcoming edition of the Sakela dance ritual. Marking the completion of the paddy harvest and the migration of people and birds from higher altitudes (udhauli) to lower warmer areas, the festival is a vibrant expression of gratitude to Mother Earth (Bhumi) and ancestral spirits for bountiful crops and protection. Communities gather at sacred Sakela grounds (usually open fields with a central Sili tree or altar), where priests (nakchhong) perform the ritual worship known as Sili Chhummi, followed by the rhythmic Sakela (Sili) dance performed in circles by men and women dressed in traditional attire while singing ancient oral hymns (mundhum) that recount creation myths, nature worship, and the cycle of life. The dance imitates farming activities, bird movements, and daily life, symbolizing harmony with nature and continuity of Kirat identity. Sakela Udhauli not only reinforces cultural pride and social bonds among the Kirat people but also serves as a living repository of their indigenous faith, cosmology, and ancestral knowledge passed down through generations.', 'Happy Sakela', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'happy-sakela', '', '', '2025-12-03 21:56:08', '2025-12-04 02:56:08', '', 0, 'http://localhost/ukroa/?post_type=tribe_events&#038;p=520', 0, 'tribe_events', '', 0),
